<br>
At any rate, I thought &quot;Recommended Level&quot; meant the stats scaled up to that level (i.e. it was still equippable below that level at reduced effect), whereas the CT stuff has hard level limits.<br>
<br>
Personally I'm fine with hard level limits, if they permit getting rid of 80% of the pointless NO DROP flags.<br>
<br>
Course to support that VI needs to have broader content (i.e. more zones) available at the middle and upper level game so you aren't stopped by farmers monopolizing all the spawns like in the bad old days of lower guk.<br>
<br>
But bottom line, NO DROP stinks.  It causes items to collect uselessly in banks or be destroyed to no end.  It doesn't let groups or guilds migrate their hard work to other people.  <br>
<br>
I'd much rather get say, a Fleshgrinder, then some point later upgrading to a Horn of Hsagra or suchlike, and being able to pass the Fleshgrinder to a guildmate who is in need of such a weapon upgrade.  If everything was NO DROP then items just go to waste.<br>
<br>
NO DROP should be reserved to designated &quot;Special loot&quot; that should only be gotten by people who have done what is required to get it (e.g. certain prestige quest rewards such as epics, perhaps &quot;hard&quot; encounter areas such as ntov, but even that could go away if there was enough such highend content to feed the high level players such that they could trade items from ToV for items from the Temple of Rallos Zek for example).<br>
<br>
The biggest issue against removing NO DROP is farming and twinking.  Twinking is somewhat of an issue but all it really does is make the lower level game go by faster for those who want it to go by faster.  Hard level limits solve this.<br>
<br>
Farming is harder, and is only solvable by having enough content at all levels of play to keep the players happy (so you don't have that special item X that EVERYONE 'needs' available in one single location), and to provide enough influx of valuables/tradables that even if you wanted to camp Fleshgrinder and someone else beat you there, you could go camp Nosepiercer to trade for it.<br>
<br>
CT is a step in the right direction.  The dungeon is challenging for a single group, and the sheer fact that it isn't camped six ways from sunday like sebilis means that the rewards, so far, balance the risk.  If it were easy, it would be packed.  Instead many's the time there are 6 people in CT: my party.  <br>
<br>
